https://crypto.stackexchange.com/questions/35440/why-does-rsa-need-p-and-q-to-be-prime-numbers

So, to make factoring as difficult as possible, you want the prime factors to be as large as possible, which means you want N to have the fewest factors possible. With ğ‘ p and ğ‘ q prime, ğ‘ N has two factors. With ğ‘ p and ğ‘ q composite, ğ‘ N has at least four factors, possibly more.

(Also, e.g. RSA is defined in terms of prime numbers, see Euler PHI (even though it is replaced by Carmichaels Totient).)

    https://crypto.stackexchange.com/questions/29591/lcm-versus-phi-in-rsa
